1. Dengue NS1 antigen is a highly conserved glycoprotein that is present at high concentration in the sera of dengue infected
patients during early clinical phase of the disease.
2. NS1 antigen is found from the first day and upto 9 days after the onset of illness in cases of primary or secondary dengue
3. Positive test indicates exposure to and infection with Dengue virus.
4. Negative result can occur if the quantity of NS1 antigen present in the specimen is below the detection limits of the assay

-ANAMNESTIC REACTION :-Persons suffered from enteric fever in the past or who had
received TAB vaccine may show agglutinins in moderate titres when suffering from
unrelated illness like viral infections. Such response can be differentiated from true
infection by demonstrating the rise in titres when test is repeated after few days.
-Test may be negative if blood sample is collected early in course of disease or if
antibody response is blunted by early administration of antibiotics.
